What ?¶

In this notebook, we'll try to analyse data about the biggest prize in cinema, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences Awards, also knows as the Oscars.

Why¶

Mainly because I couldn't think of anything else. But also because making predictions using data is fun !

For those who're not on the know, and as it's the case for any sort of major competitions, major betting activity goes on about the results of these awards. From studios who want to know how much to spend on advertisement campaigns to push their candidates in the awards race, to cinephiles who want their favorites to win, to actors and directors whom careers can be shaped by the a nod in the right category, to gambling addicts who actually put money on several outcomes and expect returns on their investment, a lot is at stake.

What's interesting is the fact that, even though these awards should award excellence in artistic fields, some people turned predicting the results of these awards into a science of sorts (and go as far as calling themselves Oscarologists !). I will try to reproduce some of the general commmon "rules of thumb" in Oscarology into data-driven, statistical statements that befit the Scientific Methodology course.

How ?¶

The idea is to use all sorts of movie metadata, as well as the history of several categories and the outcome of other awards that preceed the Oscars to make the right bet in the right category.

1. The Data¶

Gathering the right data for this task is both straightforward and tricky. The upside is that movie data is usually open and available in several forms (although rarely in immediately exploitable packages), so the first step is to define the questions we want to answer and then gather and format the data for further analysis.

I've started with the dataset from this Kaggle challenge which is provided by the Academy itself : https://www.kaggle.com/theacademy/academy-awards

It contains data on Oscar winners and nominees in all categories since 1927, which is the year the first Oscars were held. We'll use Pandas to manipulate the data and MatPlotLib to do most visualizations.

The data provided here is quite rudimental : for each year, we get a list of entries, each corresponding to a nomination in a given category (the Award column), the name of the movie the nominee (the Name column), and the movie they're nominated for (the Film column). A win is designated by a "1.0" in the Winner column.

In order to get metadata for each film, we need to do some cleanup first ! Throughout their history, awards categories have been modified, added and dropped. Since our objective is to understand future trends, we're more interested in the "modern version" of each category.

Now here we'll have to do some manual intervention to make the data more uniform. We'll define, for each modern category, a list of older names for it and update the dataframe accordingly : (I have left out the technical awards (Special Effects, Sound Mixing) because they are not as "noteworthy" as the main awards, sorry behind-the-scenes guys and girls !)

In [5]:
aliases = {"Actor in a Leading Role" : ["Actor"],
           "Actress in a Leading Role" : ["Actress"],
           "Directing" : ["Directing (Comedy Picture)","Directing (Dramatic Picture)"],
           "Best Picture" : ["Best Motion Picture", "Unique and Artistic Picture", "Outstanding Motion Picture", 
                             "Outstanding Picture", "Outstanding Production"],
           "Foreign Language Film" : ["Special Foreign Language Film Award", "Honorary Foreign Language Film Award"],
           "Writing" : categories[94:]}

modern_names = dict()
for a in aliases :
    for category in aliases[a] : modern_names[category] = a

I had to modify the original file and replace commas with tabs as separators .. it worked :)

For some reason in this category, the production company takes over the Film column while the movie's name is in the Name, no big deal !

Now to get more information about each of these movies, we'll need a new source of data. There are many great options for that, depending on the kind of questions you'd want to have answers for. Here's a list : http://www.zanmel.com/2015/12/14/10-great-datasets-on-movies/

Because the original Oscars dataset doesn't have unique identifiers for the movies (usually their IMDB url or id), we'll have to add that manually and hope for the best! Movie names aren't usually great identifiers (case in point : the first entry in the dataframe is a nomination for "The Racket", which happens to be the name of two productions : one in 1951 and one in 1929, which is the one we're looking for !).

Since there is a lot (and I mean, a lot) of movie data in most movie datasets, and since we're only interested in a subset of characteristics over a very small subset of movies, a quick way to get the data is to use a free API like this one : http://www.omdbapi.com/

This will enable us to get a number of charactersitics for each movie we have in our dataset, so that we can create a new, richer dataframe we can start working on !

The process -while successful !- isn't perfectly smooth, because for many movies the year of production and nomination don't match. Entries for several movies had to be manually updated (by querying http://www.omdbapi.com using the identifier from IMDB) These entries are :

- Th Invaders (1941) was renamed 49th Parallel for some reason
- Sunset Boulevard (1950) is listed as Sunset Blvd.

Let's now switch to a a new feature

Ratings¶

Oscar-winning movies should be great, right ? Now to assess this greatness with an "objective" score, we can use IMDB's rating as a good indicator of a movie's appeal to audiences. This is usually contrasted with movie critics opinions (journalists who review movies for a job !) which tend to be more artsy and "serious" (a movie like The Avengers and Transformers, as much of crowd pleasers they can be, tend to disappoint critics), which can be represented by what's called a metascore, which is basically an aggregation of a wide group of reviewers (and unlike the Tomato Score from RottenTomatoes, it doesn't represent the percentage of reviewers who thought that a movie is "fresh" (not bad) but it's an actual grade on a scale from 0 to 100).

Let's start by getting a general view of audiences' reaction to Oscar nominated/winning movies : Two caveats : these ratings are recent and represent a movie's reception both before and after receiving the nomination/win, which means it can't be used as an indicator to make solid predictions (there is no data available showing movie scores before and after nominations/wins). The second caveat is that "Oscar type movies" are rarely watched by big audiences, and the people who go and watch them are more inclined to like them, which makes these ratings skewed in favor of these movies a little bit. In other words, the voting "pool" is not the same for popular and award-type movies.

Genre Bias¶

One of the recurrent critiques of the Oscars is that they tend to value "important" films, meaning movies that have some gravitas, a message and generally emotionally piercing. Which leaves other "entertaining" movies in the dust, much to audiences chagrin ! What's called Genre movies (basically everything except Drama, Comedies and Musicals) tend to get the cold shoulder from the oscars, let's see what the data says! The genre Column

So the biggest B.O. number holds for Avatar (also the highest grossing movie of all times), while the highest grossing Oscar winner is The Lord of the Rings: The Return of the King. Lowest grossing Oscar winning movie is The Hurt Locker, with only $15M domestically.

This information should be necessarily coupled with information about the actual budget of the movie. For example, Avatar was made on a \$240M budget and made \$750M in the US B.O (a RoI of 3.1), while famously, last year's winner Moonlight went to gross \$65M on a \$1.5M (a factor of 43 !). This would be a nice thing to study if we had the appropriate data !

Another thing that movie geeks use to predict the awards output is to correlate it with the awards preceding the Oscars (called Precursors), notably the Guild awards. For example, the Actors' Guild Awards is a good indicator on who's going to win in the acting categories, and so on. Having these correlations in mind would certainly help elevate or eliminate certains outcomes, if only we had the appropriate data !

2.2. Actors¶

Now there is a lot to be said about the acting categories, especially in the light of what's happening now in the world and in Hollywood with the #metoo anti-harrassement movement. A lot of stereotypes are pegged on how male and female acting categories are treated, with specific demographics and characteristics of the actors and the role they play tend to determine the outcome, not necessarily how good they played it comparatively (which is, of course, impossible to objectively quantify). For example, and this is sadly true (this seems to change lately), almost every Black actor or actress ever nominated for an Academy acting award did so on a role in which they either play a slave/caretaker or a poor/ghetto-type character. This doesn't seem to be the case at all for their White counterparts. It would be infinitely more interesting to analyse these data with a more descriptive set of data points about race, roles and specific circumstances for given years, but for now

But since I don't have that kind of data (actually, I couldn't find any dataset about actors except for a complete old-ish dump of IMDB's Mongo database that needed to be set up and queried .. and then again I don't know if information about race and role-types would be there), I decided to collect a little one for one critereon which is age, the only one I could find really. I did so by querying DBPedia, which is the first time I used knowledge from one course (Semantic Web) in another!

So DBPedia contains all sorts of information about all sorts of things in a neat graph structure, with nodes representing either individuals or concepts or just values. These nodes are annotated which makes querying easy and even fun ! So I picked a random Actor (http://dbpedia.org/page/Michael_Fassbender) (who may or may not be my favorite) and scrolled through the kind of annotations he had to see what could be useful for my query. It turns out that actors are annotated with the dbr:Actor class from the http://purl.org/linguistics/gold/hypernym ontology (actresses with dbr:Actress), and their linked to their Name information with the foaf:name relation and their birth date with dbo:birthDate. Informations such as nationality and height (could be fun :) ), also can be found, but not for all actors and actresses. This DBPedia source could be mined further for more detailed information if enough time is spent to enumerate all relevant annotations (if you want to know how many GermanMaleVideoGameActors, or actors of german descent who also did some voice acting role in a Video Game, were ever nominated or won an Oscar) .. maybe another time !

So let's get that data ! We use SPARQL to query RDF-type data from DBPedia, who are kind enough to actually give direct access to all of their data via a direct interface, for no charge! Here's the link : http://dbpedia.org/sparql

And here's the query (be sure to switch output type to CSV for easier consumption !)

select ?actor ?name ?birthDate ?height ?nationality where { ?actor dbr:Actor; foaf:name ?name; OPTIONAL { ?actor dbo:height ?height. } OPTIONAL { ?actor dbo:birthDate ?birthDate. } OPTIONAL { ?actor dbo:height ?height } FILTER (?v in (dbr:Actor, dbr:Actress)) }

But this is relatively easy to manage, we'll just keep information about the birthYear (it exists as a relation in DBPedia, but it's not specified for many actors, so I took the birthDate instead), and we'll concatenate values for different nationalities into one column :

In [60]:
actor_data = {}
for name in df_actors_raw['name'].unique():
    nationalities = set()
    year, height = 0, 0
    for i, row in df_actors_raw[df_actors_raw['name'] == name].iterrows():
        try: 
            if pd.isnull(row['birthDate']) : year = np.NaN
            else: 
                try: year = int(row['birthDate'][:4])
                except: year = int(row['birthDate'][4:])
            height = row['height']
            nationalities.add('' if pd.isnull(row['nationality']) else row['nationality'].split('/')[-1].split('_')[0]) #we take the first word from the nationality URI : British_People => British
        except:
            print(row)
            print(row['nationality'])
    actor_data[name] = {'year': year, 'nationalities': ', '.join(nationalities), 'height': height}
    
print(actor_data['Michael Fassbender'])

127/906 .. That's .. discouraging to say the least.

A quick lookaround and I found out that different actors are labeled under different categories (dbr:Actor is the one I used for my query, but there is also dbr:Actress, umbel-rc:Actor ..), but most, and I mean most, are just not returned by the query (for example, Frances McDormand is indeed flagged as a dbr:Actress, but the query to list all dbr:Actress nodes simply doesn't return her).

Extraordinary circumstances call for extraordinary measures. So let's do this brute-force style ! I'm going to run a query to list every actor who's "name" property in DBPedia matches the name of the actor in my original dataframe. Since we only have 1668 actors and actresses, this won't be very hard to do (although very not elegant).

I generated the query body here :

In [66]:
for name in df_actors['Name'].unique()[:10] :
    print('"'+name+'"@en', end=', ')

"Richard Barthelmess"@en, "Emil Jannings"@en, "Louise Dresser"@en, "Janet Gaynor"@en, "Gloria Swanson"@en, "George Bancroft"@en, "Warner Baxter"@en, "Chester Morris"@en, "Paul Muni"@en, "Lewis Stone"@en,

And the query looks like this : (each time the list is modified and a CSV file is downloaded)

select ?actor ?name ?birthDate ?height ?nationality where { ?actor ?v; foaf:name ?name. OPTIONAL { ?actor dbo:height ?height. } OPTIONAL { ?actor dbo:birthDate ?birthDate. ?birthDate rdf:type xsd:date} OPTIONAL { ?actor dbo:birthDate ?birthDate. } OPTIONAL { ?actor dbo:nationality ?nationality. } FILTER (?name IN ("Richard Barthelmess"@en, "Emil Jannings"@en, "Louise Dresser"@en, "Janet Gaynor"@en, "Gloria Swanson"@en, "George Bancroft"@en, "Warner Baxter"@en, "Chester Morris"@en, "Paul Muni"@en, "Lewis Stone"@en ..)) FILTER (?v in (dbr:Actor, dbr:Actress)) }

Without adding the (Actor, Actress) restriction, the DBPedia returns all people with similar names but different professions. So I opted for the restriction which limits the results (for actors who are not annotated) but we at least get accurate results. I got 651/906 actors, I wanted a little bit more to have statically significat results.

I dropped the Actor annotation, got back some results and manually removed non-actors (the ones it says so on their URL, such as http://dbpedia.org/resource/Kevin_McCarthy_(director)), which amounted to this :

actor_data = {}
for name in df_actors_raw['name'].unique():
    nationalities = set()
    year, height = 0, 0
    for i, row in df_actors_raw[df_actors_raw['name'] == name].iterrows():
        try: 
            if pd.isnull(row['birthDate']) : year = np.NaN
            else: 
                try: year = int(row['birthDate'][:4])
                except: year = int(row['birthDate'][4:])
            height = row['height']
            nationalities.add('' if pd.isnull(row['nationality']) else row['nationality'].split('/')[-1].split('_')[0]) #we take the first word from the nationality URI : British_People => British
        except:
            print(row)
            print(row['nationality'])
    actor_data[name] = {'year': year, 'nationalities': ', '.join(nationalities), 'height': height}

#GiveLeoHisDamnOscar¶

Last year, there was a lot of compaining for Leonardo DiCaprio to win his Oscar, because he was nominated 4 times before, only to fall short every single time. He had to eat actual raw bison liver to finally get the biggest recognition an actor could wish for : winning his damn oscar. Now is Leo the unluckiest of them all ? Let's see the history of some unlucky people who may need some compaining as well: (aka people who were nominated several times yet never won) :

In [80]:
num_losses_before_win = dict()
for name in df_actors['Name'].unique():
    # To know whether someone never won, it suffices to count the sum of the "Winner" column, which should add up to 0 for "No Win"
    wins = df_actors[df_actors['Name'] == name]['Winner'].fillna(0).nonzero()[0] 
    if len(wins) > 0 :
        if min(wins) in num_losses_before_win : num_losses_before_win[min(wins)] += 1
        else: num_losses_before_win[min(wins)] = 1

In [81]:
num_losses_without_win = dict()
for name in df_actors['Name'].unique():
    # To know whether someone never won, it suffices to count the sum of the "Winner" column, which should add up to 0 for "No Win"
    noms = df_actors[df_actors['Name'] == name]['Winner'].fillna(0)
    if sum(noms) == 0 :
        if len(noms) in num_losses_without_win : num_losses_without_win[len(noms)] += 1
        else: num_losses_without_win[len(noms)] = 1

So 185 actors, that's about 63%, got their first Oscar on their first nomination, lucky bunch ! About a third of that (20%) get their oscar on their second nomination, and it keeps dwindling and dwindling.

The number of nominations without win shows us that a lot of people (almost 80%) get their one nomination and never see their name in the award broadcast again, which means that new having one nomination doesn't correlate well with having eventually more nominations (only 20% of nominees get to be nominated a second time or more : and they have an almost equal chance on winning on their second nomination (around 20% for both graphs).

In general, and countrary to popular belief, having multiple nominations doesn't realistically increase your chances of winning again ! (graphs for winning after X nominations and not winning after X nominations have the same shape !)

Now this is what sexism looks like, statistically speaking. Men to be generally immune against the effect of aging, being able to score awards years past peak performance (~40), especially in the Supporting category (which is now sometimes ironically called "Lifetime Achievement" category because it's usually given to older actors who've done a lot in their careers but never legitimately won). This generosity, however, doesn't extend to women. As the histogrames show, women have their best shot at winning while they're still "young and attractive", which is consistent with the demography of the 6400 Academy voters (who are revealed publicly so as not to be bribed, but are known to be at least mostly old, mostly white and and mostly men). After the age of 40 (which is about the "shelf life" of most actors, falling out of celebrity and making room to the new generation), women just don't seem to crack the wins.

Except if you're Meryl Streep.

3. Conclusion, further work and predictions ?¶

So this was fun ! (Except the data cleaning part which was whatever the opposite of fun is)

A lot of the observed results were mere confirmations of well-known phenomena for the Awards observers (Genre bias, movie length, critical acclaim, actresses ages ..) but others were genuinely surprising (the higher correlation between audience scores and a movie's likelihood to win an oscar, longest losing streaks, movie duration through time ..).

There is a lot that could be studied on Oscarology if more data was available (most notably how the Oscar correlates with other awards that have different/niche voting groups, like Directors Guild Award or the Golden Globes) which can theoretically be collected directly from the IMDB pages of these awards and a some heavy manual formatting. What would be more interesting, though, is to see the impact of winning / getting nominations on the finantial performance of a movie and the career of its cast and crew (how much a typical actor makes vs how much an Oscar-Winning Actor makes, for example).

Another aspect that is really interesting, but pretty impossible to model, is the zeitgeist effect. The Oscars tend to prefer movies that are 'important' over ones that are 'technically better' when the choice has to be made. In times of Wars, movies about heroism and sacrifice were always selected (and since the US is kinda continuously in war somewhere, at least one movie every year should be about war, preferably against Nazi Germany and where the US saves everyone).

2017, for example, already labeled the Year of the Woman, has seen in the light of the sexual misconduct allegations coming from all sides, a chance to open the debate about sexism in the movie industry. We showed one aspect of sexism when it comes to awards (women need to be singificantly younger than their male counterpart to win an acting award). That's why it's agreed on, this year, that the winning movie will be lead by a female character, which didn't happen since 2004's Million Dollar Baby, 13 YEARS ago). Capturing this kind of context is really hard to do in a model, especially since there can be a lot of relevant themes every year (think racism, immegration and sexual identity as the hot topics of the couple last two years).

On the actors side, a lot can be done as well. The #OscarSoWhite controvery a couple years ago (where all nominees in all acting categories + director were all white) made such waves that the Academy was forced make substantial changes in its voting body, which somehow resulted in last year's Moonlight's surprising win, the first movie ever with an entire black cast to win the big award (not out of charity, since it held a perfect Metascore for a very long time). Analysing race data, especially with regard to the type of roles and characters. This dataset can also be done, but it would require more patience than what I have for the couple weeks to come !

The analysis can and should be extended to the other categories, but that's even harder given how sparse the data was for actors (which are consider celebrities), let alone Special Effect technicians.

In the end, these are just statistics. It would take more than superficial data analysis to understand the behavior of a collective hivemind such as the Academy. That's why, in the end, we just make predictions and hope for the best (/most likely) to win !
